Thailand: Dengue Alert for Travellers from Shanghai to Bangkok
------------------------------------------------
With dengue fever once again causing a health scare in Thailand, residents
[of Shanghai] planning to visit the country should take steps to prevent
mosquito bites, officials with the Shanghai Entry-Exit Inspection and
Quarantine Bureau warned yesterday. In January 2003 alone, health officials
in Thailand discovered some 800 cases of dengue fever in and around
Bangkok, according to the Xinhua news agency. Health authorities in Bangkok
are predicting more people could catch the disease this year than in 2001,
when fear of dengue fever caused panic among Shanghai people who planned to
travel to the country.
The fever, which is spread by mosquitoes, is a viral infection causing skin
rash, headaches, fever and extreme pain. But a more dangerous version of
the disease, dengue hemorrhagic fever, can be [fatal]. "So far the state
entry-exit bureau has not issued a warning especially for this epidemic
yet," said Lu Feng with the Shanghai bureau. Unlike in 2001, when many
local residents canceled their trips to Thailand, this year's outbreak has
caused no cancellations, according to 3 local travel agencies contacted by
Shanghai Daily. "We have received no cancellation or questions from
customers so far," said Liu Xiaojun with the Shanghai China Youth Travel
Service Co. "Few locals have changed their plans probably because they know
little about the epidemic situation," said Liu.
Officials with the bureau warn that people who have travelled to Thailand
recently should go to the hospital immediately if they get a fever or
headache, while people who are going to the country should wear long-sleeve
clothes and carry mosquito repellent.
