Ecuador: Dengue Hemorrhagic Fever Reaches Epidemic Levels
-------------------------------------------------
Dengue hemorrhagic fever has reached epidemic levels in Ecuador, as heavy
rains pound the Pacific coast and make it tough to control the deadly
disease, a health official said on Wed 19 Feb 2003. This cash-strapped
Andean nation declared a sanitary emergency a week ago in a bid to channel
funds to fumigate coastal regions and treat patients with the potentially
lethal dengue hemorrhagic fever.
National Health Director Javier Carrillo told Reuters that the disease had
already reached epidemic proportions with 22 cases so far this year. [This
figure represents an increase in 8 cases since Thu 13 Feb 2003 and exceeds
by 2 the total number of cases recorded during the whole of 2002. - Mod.CP]
Dengue is endemic to Ecuador's coastal region and flourishes during the wet
months of December through April. The disease's main symptoms include
fever, headache, joint pain, nausea, vomiting, and rash. Patients with
dengue hemorrhagic fever also may experience internal bleeding.
