From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Chicago Tribune, KRT Newsfeatures, Thu 20 Feb 2003 [edited]
<http://www.bradenton.com/mld/bradenton/news/world/5222866.htm>

Mexico: Dengue Fever Outbreak in Puerto Vallarta
------------------------------------------------
As the tourists relax and sip margaritas around the hotel pools, the
hard-working residents of this balmy vacation spot are engaged in a far
different activity to restore their peace of mind. The hotel maids and
margarita servers are being encouraged to clean up the patios of their
hillside homes, which overlook the famous strip of beach resorts. As
mundane as that sounds, it actually could be a matter of sickness or
health. At least according to Mexican health officials trying to contain an
outbreak of dengue fever -- or what is more descriptively known as
"breakbone fever" -- that has killed 2 and immobilized hundreds in the
resort city's poorer neighborhoods in recent months.
To contain the mosquito-borne virus, health officials have determined that
the best strategy is not expensive fumigating or hunting for an elusive
vaccine. Rather, it's persuading city dwellers to get rid of or cover up
the old tires, cases of empty soda bottles, bird baths, and collectibles
that clutter many yards. That eliminates the standing water in which
mosquitoes breed. And that, residents are told, reduces the spread of the
incredibly painful and sometimes fatal malady that strikes more than a
million people worldwide each year. Judging by the new tidiness of yards in
the poor Jardines neighborhood here, residents appear to be responding to
Operation Clean Patio, a campaign health workers have waged street-to-street.
In Mexico in 2002, more than 3700 people were hit by symptoms of aching
joints and searing headaches, and at least 4 of the victims died. Dengue
fever was thought to have been mostly wiped out in the 1970s. But patches
remained in Venezuela and the Caribbean, and with the help of the fever's
host mosquitoes, it has been making a comeback. Health officials say the
risk of dengue spreading into the United States is low because of North
Americans' more indoor, air-conditioned lifestyle. But there have been
outbreaks along the US-Mexico border, and a suspected 200 cases were
reported around the city of Matamoros last year.
The Puerto Vallarta area had not had a case of dengue in 3 years. But since
the fall, health officials have treated 346 cases, including 32 cases of
the potentially lethal dengue hemorrhagic fever. 2 people died in the city,
while 2 others died in the Gulf Coast state of Quintana Roo. Health
officials said the cases were isolated until Hurricane Kenna struck the
Puerto Vallarta area in late October, inundating the city with heavy rains
and a massive wave surge that dumped sailboats in back yards, filled hotel
pools with beach sand, and left pools of water everywhere. Health officials
said the outbreak did not affect tourist areas, mostly because of better
sanitation precautions around the hotels. But there have been cases of
American tourists contracting the virus in Mexican resorts and bringing it
home with them.
[Byline: Hugh Dellios]
